// Golden fixtures: REAL gcc-produced ELF64 relocatable objects carrying
// SECTION-RELATIVE relocations -- c167, D-LK-STATIC-LINK-SECTION-RELATIVE-
// RELOC. Embedded byte-for-byte so the reader's section-relative resolution
// is deterministic + CI-portable (no gcc at test time). gcc 13, x86_64, -O0.
//
//   gccStrlitObject()   -- `const char *dss_greet(void){ return "hello world"; }`
//     The string lives in `.rodata` (12 bytes) with NO symbol of its own;
//     dss_greet references it via `R_X86_64_PC32 .rodata-4` (the .rodata
//     SECTION symbol). The reader must reconstruct the anonymous bytes as a
//     synthetic gap atom and redirect the reference to it (residual 0).
//
//   gccAnswerJumpTableObject() -- TWO functions in one `.text` (no
//     -ffunction-sections): `lib_pad` first, then `lib_answer` (a 6-case
//     `switch`, returns 42) at a NON-ZERO .text offset. gcc emits an anonymous
//     24-byte jump table in `.rodata`: `.rela.text` has 2 section-relative lea
//     refs to it, and `.rela.rodata` has 6 entries each `R_X86_64_PC32
//     .text+<off>` -- INTERIOR references that fall inside lib_answer. The
//     reader must (a) reconstruct the jump table as a gap atom, (b) redirect
//     the lea refs to it, and (c) SELECT lib_answer (not lib_pad) for the
//     interior entries via the data-section-PC-relative search offset. The
//     two-function layout LOCKS the atom-selection path.

